{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}
{{Use British English|date=August 2015}}
{{BLP sources|date=April 2011}}
{{notability|bio|date=January 2014}}
'''Richard Millington''' is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[birders|birder]] and [[bird artist]]. He lives in [[Cley-next-the-Sea]], [[Norfolk]] with his wife Hazel.

He is assistant editor of ''[[Birding World]]'' magazine. His contributions to that journal include many articles on [[bird identification]]. He also runs [[Birdline]], a [[telephone information service]] containing news of rare birds.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=G6FfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=BTIMAAAAIBAJ&pg=2615,4280124&dq=richard+millington+bird&hl=en|title=Rare bird enchants England|date=30 May 1990|work=[[Lewiston Morning Tribune]]|accessdate=24 April 2011}}</ref>

Richard Millington is also a [[twitcher]]. He is one of a small number of [[birders]] who have seen over 500 species in [[UK|Britain]].{{cn|date=January 2014}} He also found the UK's first Rock Sparrow at Cley on 14 June 1981, still the only record in the UK. In 1980 he undertook a [[yearlisting|yearlist]], at a time when this form of twitching was still in its infancy, seeing 300 species of bird in the wild in Britain throughout the course of the year, and his illustrated book ''A Twitcher's Diary'' catalogues his birding travels during that year.

